F9.fix_sketch:
Rust-only fix (Python is the reference implementation and already correct, so byte-parity means making Rust match fnmatch semantics). In crates/clankerprof-core/src/targets.rs, rewrite `glob_to_regex` to translate bracket classes the way CPython's fnmatch.translate does instead of escaping them:

fn glob_to_regex(pattern: &str) -> String {
    let chars: Vec<char> = pattern.chars().collect();
    let mut output = String::from("^");
    let mut i = 0;
    while i < chars.len() {
        match chars[i] {
            '*' => output.push_str(".*"),
            '?' => output.push('.'),
            '[' => {
                // fnmatch rules: optional leading '!' then optional literal ']'
                // belong to the class; scan for the closing ']'.
                let mut j = i + 1;
                if j < chars.len() && chars[j] == '!' { j += 1; }
                if j < chars.len() && chars[j] == ']' { j += 1; }
                while j < chars.len() && chars[j] != ']' { j += 1; }
                if j >= chars.len() {
                    output.push_str("\\["); // unmatched '[' stays literal (fnmatch parity)
                } else {
                    let stuff: String = chars[i + 1..j].iter().collect::<String>().replace('\\', "\\\\");
                    output.push('[');
                    if let Some(rest) = stuff.strip_prefix('!') {
                        output.push('^');
                        output.push_str(rest);
                    } else {
                        if stuff.starts_with('^') || stuff.starts_with('[') { output.push('\\'); }
                        output.push_str(&stuff);
                    }
                    output.push(']');
                    i = j;
                }
            }
            c @ ('.' | '+' | '(' | ')' | '|' | '^' | '$' | '{' | '}' | ']' | '\\') => {
                output.push('\\');
                output.push(c);
            }
            c => output.push(c),
        }
        i += 1;
    }
    output.push('$');
    output
}

For strict fnmatch fidelity also handle the degenerate classes CPython special-cases: empty `[]...` (fnmatch scans past a first `]`, so `[]a]` is a class containing `]` and `a` — covered above), `[!]` -> `.`, empty stuff -> `(?!)`, and escape regex set-op chars `&~|` inside the class. No Python change. Accompany with: (a) new parity cases in tests/test_clankerprof_rust_parity.py exercising bracket-class globs (positive `[ab]`, negative `[!ab]`, unmatched `[`) through targets, slices, and scopes (scopes.rs:239 shares the matcher); (b) matching Rust unit tests in targets.rs; (c) a row/note in docs/CLANKERPROF_PARITY.md recording fnmatch-compatible glob semantics. Per CLAUDE.md the behavior lands in Python and Rust together — here Python needs no code change, only the shared test coverage.

